text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!Idioma de Señas de Nicaragua%0a%0a:Author: vincent_c%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe Birth of a New Language%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI first learned about Nicaraguan sign language and its development through a recent Youtube video (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1xd3IdYXdow&ab_channel=HalfasInteresting). The language developed naturally with no outside guidance starting in the 1970s in Nicaragua. Prior to the 1970s, deaf individuals in Nicaragua had very little contact with each other, and it wasn't until the first deaf schools were opened that deaf kids could interact with each other. The teachers' attempts at teaching lipreading, spoken Spanish, and basic sign language for spelling failed, but the students rapidly developed their own sign language to communicate with each other. With a large disconnect in communication between school staff and the students, American sign linguist Judy Kegl was contacted, and she began analyzing the language the children had created. She noted that younger children had taken the simpler pidgin-like language of the older students and added further complexity.%0a%0aNow known as Idioma de Señas de Nicaragua, the language was a very unique studying experience in the world of linguistics, as it was the first time a completely new, spontaneous language could be analyzed. It serves as proof, for some linguists, that language acquisition is an innate ability for humans.%0a%0aSource: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicaraguan_Sign_Language%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[